  "doc_id": "1327",
  "text": "Although the proteins forming the exocytotic fusion pore have not yet been identified, our results indicate that proteins control not only the formation but also the subsequent expansion of the fusion pore. At this stage, the fusion pore is modulated by PKC-and Ca 2ϩ -binding proteins. Fusion pore control may be important specifically in neurosecretion where transmitter release is performed in a cycle of rapid exo-endocytosis [CITATION_1] and where staurosporine also inhibits collapse of vesicles into the plasma membrane [CITATION_2] . It was shown recently that synaptic vesicles retain their identity through the endocytic cycle [CITATION_3] , suggesting that the fusion pore may remain under tight control allowing for exo-endocytosis without complete incorporation of the vesicle into the plasma membrane.",
